Vladimir Putin and the risk of a Third World War
SAN FRANCISCO – Russia's invasion of Ukraine on February 24 marked the beginning of a third world war that has the potential to destroy our civilization.
The invasion was preceded by a long meeting between Russian President Vladimir Putin and Chinese President Xi Jinping on February 4 – at the beginning of the celebrations for the Chinese Lunar New Year and the Beijing Winter Olympics.
At the end of this meeting, the two men published a 5,000-word document, carefully written, announcing a close partnership between their two countries.
The document is stronger than any treaty and certainly required meticulous preparatory negotiations.
I was surprised to see that Xi seems to have given Putin a free hand to invade and go to war against Ukraine.
He must be very confident and regard his later confirmation as lifelong leader of China as a mere formality.
After concentrating all power in his hands, Xi carefully prepared the scenario in which he would be elevated to the level of Mao Zedong and Deng Xiaoping.
After securing Xi's support, Putin set out to realize his life's dream with incredible brutality.
As he approaches his 70th birthday, Putin believes that if he wants to impose his mark on Russian history, it is now or never.
But his conception of Russia's role in the world is distorted.
He seems to believe that the Russian people need a tsar whom they can follow blindly.
This is precisely the opposite of a democratic society - and it is a view that distorts the Russian "soul," emotional to the point of sensitivity.
As a child, I met many Russian soldiers on numerous occasions when they occupied Hungary in 1945.
I learned that they were willing to share their last piece of bread with you if you asked them for it.
Later, in the early 1980s, I embarked on what I call my political philanthropy.
First, I created a foundation in my native Hungary, then I actively participated in the disintegration of the Soviet empire.
When Mikhail Gorbachev came to power in 1985, the disintegration had already begun.
I created a foundation in Russia, then I did the same in each of the successor states.
In Ukraine, I created a foundation even before it became an independent country.
I also visited China in 1984, where I was the first foreigner authorized to establish a foundation (which I closed in 1989, just before the Tian'anmen Square massacre).
I do not know Putin personally, but I have closely observed his rise, being aware of his cruelty.
He destroyed the capital of Chechnya, Grozny. And he threatens to do the same with the capital of Ukraine, Kyiv.
Putin was once a clever operator of the KGB, but he seems to have changed recently.
Having developed a fixed idea, he seems to have lost touch with reality.
He certainly misjudged the situation in Ukraine.
He expected the Russian-speaking Ukrainians to welcome Russian soldiers with open arms, but they proved to be entirely on the same side as the Ukrainian-speaking population.
The Ukrainians have mounted an incredibly courageous resistance against an opponent that nothing seems to be able to stop.
In July 2021, Putin published a lengthy essay arguing that Russians and Ukrainians are really one people and that Ukrainians have been misled by neo-Nazi agitators.
The first part of his argument is not without historical justification, given that Kyiv was the original seat of the Russian Orthodox Church.
But in the second part, it was Putin who was misled.
He should have been more cautious.
Many Ukrainians fought bravely during the 'Euromaidan' demonstrations in 2014.
The events of 2014 plunged him into a black rage.
But the Russian army performed poorly when it received orders to attack its Ukrainian brothers.
The entrenched corruption in the allocation of defense contracts has also played an important role in his poor results.
Yet, instead of feeling guilty, Putin seems to have literally gone mad.
He decided to punish Ukraine for opposing him and seems to be acting without encountering any resistance.
He throws the entire Russian army into battle and ignores all the rules of war, including indiscriminately bombing the civilian population.
Many hospitals have been hit and the electrical grid supplying the Chernobyl nuclear power plant (currently occupied by Russian troops) has been damaged.
In besieged Mariupol, 400,000 people were without water and food for nearly a week.
Russia could well lose the war.
The United States and the European Union are sending defensive weapons to Ukraine, and efforts are underway to purchase Russian-made MIG fighters, which Ukrainian pilots know how to fly.
This could make all the difference.
Whatever the outcome, Putin has already done wonders in managing to strengthen the determination and unity of the EU.
Meanwhile, Xi seems to have realized that Putin is acting unilaterally.
On March 8, a day after the Chinese foreign minister Wang Yi insisted that the friendship between China and Russia remain "solid," Xi called French President Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Olaf Scholz to express his support for their efforts to restore peace.
He wished to express as much restraint as possible in the war to avoid a humanitarian crisis.
It is far from certain that Putin will accede to Xi's wishes.
We can only hope that Putin and Xi are removed before they destroy our civilization.
